==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'wɪtan/}}

===Etymology 1===
From Germanic ''*witan'' (present tense ''*wait-''), from Indo-European ''*u̯oidh₂e'', originally a perfect form of ''*u̯eid-'' ‘see’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[wita]], Old Saxon [[witan]]/{{Unicode|'''wēt'''}} (Dutch [[weten]]), Old High German [[wizzan]]/'''weiz''' (German [[wissen]]), Old Norse [[vita]]/'''veit''' (Swedish [[veta]], Gothic [[𐍅𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽]]/'''𐍅𐌰𐌹𐍄'''.  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[videre]], Baltic ''*waid-'' (Lithuanian [[vadinti]]), Slavic ''*vēde-'' (Old Church Slavonic [[вѣдѣти]], Russian [[ведать]]).

====Verb====
'''witan''' (preterite-present: {{Unicode|'''wāt'''}} ‘he knows’, '''wisse'''/'''wiste''' ‘he knew’, ('''ġe''')'''witen''' past participle)
# to be aware of, to [[know]] (something)

===Noun===
'''witan'''
* plural of [[wita]]

